AUDIENCE: --the
strength of an economy.

00:49:22.995 --> 00:49:23.460
Yeah.

00:49:23.460 --> 00:49:24.430
NOMI PRINS: Right,
and what stops it.

00:49:24.430 --> 00:49:26.730
And that's the odd thing that's
been happening over the last 10

00:49:26.730 --> 00:49:27.230
years.

00:49:27.230 --> 00:49:31.690
All of this started out as an
emergency policy 10 years ago.

00:49:31.690 --> 00:49:33.750
And obviously, the fact
that it still exists

00:49:33.750 --> 00:49:36.060
is an indication that
whatever caused that emergency

00:49:36.060 --> 00:49:37.140
hasn't really been fixed.

00:49:37.140 --> 00:49:39.306
And if you pull the plug,
yes, it will be a problem.

00:49:39.306 --> 00:49:41.070
So whether you pull
the plug on working

00:49:41.070 --> 00:49:42.528
with someone else's
currency, which

00:49:42.528 --> 00:49:43.710
these banks can't really--

00:49:43.710 --> 00:49:45.210
they trade in each
other's currency.

00:49:45.210 --> 00:49:46.501
They own each other's currency.

00:49:46.501 --> 00:49:49.590
They hold bonds in each
other's currency-- particularly

00:49:49.590 --> 00:49:51.210
the holding of the
dollar, because we

00:49:51.210 --> 00:49:52.830
have the most amount
of debt relative

00:49:52.830 --> 00:49:56.740
to the rest of their nations.

00:49:56.740 --> 00:50:00.480
And so the problem
is, if they stop,

00:50:00.480 --> 00:50:03.029
that's one way the
system could collapse.

00:50:03.029 --> 00:50:05.070
If they stop because they
don't trust each other,

00:50:05.070 --> 00:50:06.150
it's because this happens.

00:50:06.150 --> 00:50:07.774
Again, it's because
you all of a sudden

00:50:07.774 --> 00:50:10.500
have a bunch of banks
going under or having

00:50:10.500 --> 00:50:15.940
a real crisis of some sort
that's related to a derivative.

00:50:15.940 --> 00:50:20.592
It's related to derivatives
that are now partly created

00:50:20.592 --> 00:50:22.800
from corporate bonds, that
used to be mortgage bonds.

00:50:22.800 --> 00:50:24.440
And those corporate
bonds start to default,

00:50:24.440 --> 00:50:25.990
so those derivatives
start to go under.

00:50:25.990 --> 00:50:27.540
And the whole chain
starts to happen again.

00:50:27.540 --> 00:50:29.123
And they're like,
well, wait a minute.

00:50:29.123 --> 00:50:31.770
We really need to accelerate or
move away from these currencies

00:50:31.770 --> 00:50:32.700
or from each other.

00:50:32.700 --> 00:50:34.664
That is how these crises happen.

00:50:34.664 --> 00:50:36.330
It's not like this
definitive statement.

00:50:36.330 --> 00:50:37.860
Like Europe can't say, we're
never going to use the dollar.

00:50:37.860 --> 00:50:39.780
Like, it's just not
going to happen.

00:50:39.780 --> 00:50:43.050
But what they can do is they
can develop relationships

00:50:43.050 --> 00:50:45.750
outside of the dollar so
that, if something like this

00:50:45.750 --> 00:50:47.430
happens again--
