00:50:47.430 --> 00:50:50.340
it will start in the
United States again too,

00:50:50.340 --> 00:50:53.130
because we have lent a lot of
money to a lot of countries.

00:50:53.130 --> 00:50:54.810
We've done all the
complex structures.

00:50:54.810 --> 00:50:56.760
We have more at risk.

00:50:56.760 --> 00:50:59.860
And we're more codependent, in
general, related to the world

00:50:59.860 --> 00:51:01.690
than other countries are--

00:51:01.690 --> 00:51:03.820
then you could have that
fall start to happen.

00:51:03.820 --> 00:51:05.095
So it's not like a decision--

00:51:05.095 --> 00:51:06.720
we're not going to
trust your currency.

00:51:06.720 --> 00:51:08.720
It's more like, we're not
going to trust the way

00:51:08.720 --> 00:51:10.710
you deal with your system.

00:51:10.710 --> 00:51:15.480
And what happened with
the developing countries

00:51:15.480 --> 00:51:18.262
in the wake of the financial
crisis is there's--

00:51:18.262 --> 00:51:19.720
and I talk about
this in the book--

00:51:19.720 --> 00:51:21.020
there's a lot more meetings.

00:51:21.020 --> 00:51:24.072
There's a lot more conferences
amongst themselves.

00:51:24.072 --> 00:51:26.280
There's a lot more growth
in trade agreements outside

00:51:26.280 --> 00:51:28.072
of the US, and not
necessarily using Japan.

00:51:28.072 --> 00:51:29.946
And there's ones where
Japan is using Europe.

00:51:29.946 --> 00:51:32.160
There's just a lot of
realignments going on.

00:51:32.160 --> 00:51:34.910
And that's a way to say not so
much we won't use the dollar,

00:51:34.910 --> 00:51:36.660
we won't use your
currency, but we

00:51:36.660 --> 00:51:42.220
are cognizant that this is
still on kind of shaky ground.

00:51:42.220 --> 00:51:45.570
And so the next time there
is a financial crisis,

00:51:45.570 --> 00:51:48.270
hopefully, we have a
little bit more protection,

00:51:48.270 --> 00:51:49.680
sort of alternatives.

00:51:49.680 --> 00:51:51.660
Which may or may not--
it depends what happens.

00:51:51.660 --> 00:51:52.800
It depends how big that is.

00:51:52.800 --> 00:51:54.508
I mean, no one really
expected the market

00:51:54.508 --> 00:51:56.850
to be cut by, like,
45% in 2008 from where

00:51:56.850 --> 00:51:57.810
it was the year before.

00:51:57.810 --> 00:51:59.820
I mean, that wasn't
an expectation.

00:51:59.820 --> 00:52:01.320
And even now, when
I say this stuff,

00:52:01.320 --> 00:52:04.279
like that the market's
going to potentially crash,

00:52:04.279 --> 00:52:05.820
we're up at these
like heady heights,

00:52:05.820 --> 00:52:09.640
most people don't
feel the same way.

00:52:09.640 --> 00:52:10.989
But it could still happen.

00:52:10.989 --> 00:52:12.530
AUDIENCE: Like a
continuation-- maybe

00:52:12.530 --> 00:52:14.190
this is an obvious question.

00:52:14.190 --> 00:52:17.910
But then couldn't everyone
just hit the reset button

00:52:17.910 --> 00:52:19.750
and then build each
other back up again?

00:52:19.750 --> 00:52:25.890
NOMI PRINS: Well, one of the
solutions or possible paths

00:52:25.890 --> 00:52:28.920
that I talk about
in the last chapter

00:52:28.920 --> 00:52:33.630
is this idea of canceling
out each other's debt

00:52:33.630 --> 00:52:37.530
and doing it in such a way that
the countries that would be

00:52:37.530 --> 00:52:39.690
most burdened by a collapse--

00:52:39.690 --> 00:52:41.250
that were most
burdened by a collapse

00:52:41.250 --> 00:52:44.490
that they did not
cause in 2008--

00:52:44.490 --> 00:52:46.480
could be in a more
stable situation.

00:52:46.480 --> 00:52:48.000
What's happened
with all of this is

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:49.380
that the countries
that were most

00:52:49.380 --> 00:52:52.695
at the center of the
last financial crisis

00:52:52.695 --> 00:52:56.130
and have the ability to
do more harm financially

00:52:56.130 --> 00:52:58.710
are the ones that got
the most subsidies.

00:52:58.710 --> 00:53:01.430
And so that just created
more inherent risk.

00:53:01.430 --> 00:53:03.450
And again, this could
go on for a long time.

00:53:03.450 --> 00:53:05.240
But it created
more inherent risk.

00:53:05.240 --> 00:53:09.450
So that's one of the things
that could also happen.

00:53:09.450 --> 00:53:11.610
AUDIENCE: So the word
"collusion," to me anyway,

00:53:11.610 --> 00:53:14.130
has a negative connotation.

00:53:14.130 --> 00:53:16.530
Is it fair to characterize
this collusion, in your view,

00:53:16.530 --> 00:53:17.580
as something sinister?

00:53:17.580 --> 00:53:20.640
Or do these people responsible
for these systems think

00:53:20.640 --> 00:53:25.020
they're acting in a
very honorable way

00:53:25.020 --> 00:53:27.810
by saving the
economy or whatever?

00:53:27.810 --> 00:53:30.300
NOMI PRINS: Well, it's weird,
because I think most of them

00:53:30.300 --> 00:53:36.390
believe that what they're doing
is ultimately going to help

00:53:36.390 --> 00:53:41.520
the economy, even though the
evidence is that it hasn't.

00:53:41.520 --> 00:53:44.617
The evidence is that wage
growth hasn't really increased.

00:53:44.617 --> 00:53:47.200
Stock growth has increased, so
certain bonuses have increased,

00:53:47.200 --> 00:53:50.850
but the evidence is that the
economies that supposedly were

00:53:50.850 --> 00:53:53.550
fixed are really sputtering.

00:53:53.550 --> 00:53:55.140
And the economies
that didn't receive

00:53:55.140 --> 00:53:57.750
so much quantitative easing
are either doing better,

00:53:57.750 --> 00:53:59.880
or they're still
caught up in what

00:53:59.880 --> 00:54:05.270
might be the impact
of what happens here.

00:54:05.270 --> 00:54:08.860
So it's hard to say.

00:54:08.860 --> 00:54:14.650
But I think what
ultimately will happen,

00:54:14.650 --> 00:54:17.220
though, is that at some
point these people--

00:54:17.220 --> 00:54:18.750
they shift.

00:54:18.750 --> 00:54:21.960
Some of them move out and
some new people come in.

00:54:21.960 --> 00:54:23.940
Mario Draghi, at some
point, has to leave.

00:54:23.940 --> 00:54:29.880
And probably-- or possibly,
but probably whoever takes

00:54:29.880 --> 00:54:32.507
his place will come, say, from
Germany or from a country that

00:54:32.507 --> 00:54:34.590
actually is against this
policy and actually would

00:54:34.590 --> 00:54:38.702
prefer that less artificial
money is in the system.

00:54:38.702 --> 00:54:40.410
And they have political
reasons for that.

00:54:40.410 --> 00:54:41.640
Their economy's doing
better than some

00:54:41.640 --> 00:54:43.015
of the other
economies in Europe,

00:54:43.015 --> 00:54:45.210
so this had other ramifications.

00:54:45.210 --> 00:54:47.910
And so a shifting in
the actual individuals

00:54:47.910 --> 00:54:49.650
at the top of these
institutions could

00:54:49.650 --> 00:54:51.540
create a shift in the policy.

00:54:51.540 --> 00:54:53.970
But also, there's a
way to unwind this,

00:54:53.970 --> 00:54:55.860
or at least to start to
unwind, that actually

00:54:55.860 --> 00:55:02.910
is using this off-the-rails
solution in a good way.

00:55:02.910 --> 00:55:07.260
For example, the Fed could take
$1 trillion, or $2 trillion,

00:55:07.260 --> 00:55:08.790
or whatever, of
the $4.5 trillion

00:55:08.790 --> 00:55:11.130
worth of money they
created and assets

00:55:11.130 --> 00:55:13.710
they received in
return for doing that,

00:55:13.710 --> 00:55:15.180
and create an
infrastructure bank,

00:55:15.180 --> 00:55:18.240
or create a development bank,
or do something that's actually

00:55:18.240 --> 00:55:20.970
really financing
the real economy

00:55:20.970 --> 00:55:23.070
and also moving forward.

00:55:23.070 --> 00:55:27.060
When I was in China, I took the
high-speed rail from Beijing

00:55:27.060 --> 00:55:29.040
to Shanghai.

00:55:29.040 --> 00:55:33.180
And I don't know if anyone has--

00:55:33.180 --> 00:55:35.580
I mean, when you talk
"high," it's really fast.

00:55:35.580 --> 00:55:39.180
Like, you cannot
see the countryside.

00:55:39.180 --> 00:55:40.320
And it's quiet.

00:55:40.320 --> 00:55:42.620
And I mean, it's
excellent technology.

00:55:42.620 --> 00:55:44.370
I mean, obviously, it
costs what it costs,

00:55:44.370 --> 00:55:45.990
but that's the kind
of development,

00:55:45.990 --> 00:55:48.410
that's the kind of
infrastructure building--

00:55:48.410 --> 00:55:50.310
developing the
technology in conjunction

00:55:50.310 --> 00:55:55.260
with the real parts
of the economy

00:55:55.260 --> 00:55:57.870
that real people
actually work on-- that's

00:55:57.870 --> 00:55:59.244
more forward-stabilizing.

00:55:59.244 --> 00:56:01.410
So you could actually take
a lot of the money that's

00:56:01.410 --> 00:56:03.493
been created, and rather
than have it go into debt

00:56:03.493 --> 00:56:07.167
and have it go into stock,
actually have it diverted.

00:56:07.167 --> 00:56:08.750
Nobody's going to
be happy about that.

00:56:08.750 --> 00:56:09.916
It might cause a correction.

00:56:09.916 --> 00:56:12.833
But ultimately, it's a question
of long term versus short term.

00:56:12.833 --> 00:56:13.712
AUDIENCE: Thank you, so much.

00:56:13.712 --> 00:56:13.740
Nomi.

00:56:13.740 --> 00:56:14.100
NOMI PRINS: Yeah.

00:56:14.100 --> 00:56:14.500
No, thank you.

00:56:14.500 --> 00:56:15.166
Thank you, guys.

